[2] UK
Date: Thu 12 May 2022
Source: Independent [edited]
https://www.independent.co.uk/news/health/hepatitis-kids-child-outbreak-cases-b2077945.html


Thirteen more cases of mysterious hepatitis in UK
--------------------------------------------------
Thirteen more children in the UK have been found to have sudden onset hepatitis, as a child in Ireland died from the severe liver condition.

Health officials around the world are investigating a sudden rise in cases of the condition in children. The WHO said 348 probable cases of the acute form of hepatitis in children had been detected in more than 20 countries since it started monitoring the situation early in April [2022]. The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control put the global case total at 450 by [3 May 2022].

In the UK, the country which first raised the alarm of a rise in cases, the UK Health Security (UKHSA) recorded 176 child cases as of [10 May 2022], mostly in children under 5. Of the ill children, 128 lived in England, 26 in Scotland, 12 in Wales and 9 in Northern Ireland.

Eleven of the UK children needed liver transplants but none died. A child in Ireland died after being admitted to hospital as another received a liver transplant, Irish health officials said. Ireland has recorded 6 cases of hepatitis in children up to the age of 12 since April [2022].

The outbreak of cases surprised health officials the world over and a global investigation has yet to determine precisely what is causing the uptick in cases. The common viruses that cause hepatitis: hepatitis viruses A, B, C, and E; have not been detected in any of the cases reported worldwide. The WHO said the most likely cause is adenovirus, a common cause of childhood illness, though other viruses including [the one that causes] COVID-19 are being investigated. Adenovirus is the most frequently detected virus in samples tested by the UKHSA. In a briefing on [6 May 2022], the UKHSA said adenovirus was detected in 91 cases out of the 126 that had been tested. Testing of 7 children in England that needed a liver transplant found all 7 had adenovirus.

[Byline: Liam James]

