[3] Mexico
Date: Thu 12 May 2022
Source: El Pais [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
https://elpais.com/mexico/2022-05-12/confirmados-los-primeros-cuatro-casos-de-hepatitis-aguda-infantil-en-mexico.html


First 4 cases of acute childhood hepatitis confirmed in Mexico
--------------------------------------------------------------
The 1st 4 cases of acute childhood hepatitis in Mexico have been detected in the state of Nuevo LeÃ³n, as reported on Thursday [12 May 2022], by the state Health Secretariat. The patients are stable and remain under continuous medical surveillance to monitor their progress. "We have received the report of 4 patients in different public and private institutions. So far, all stable. They are children of different ages," said the head of the unit, Ana Rosa MarroquÃ­n Escamilla, at a press conference.

The official has not given more details of the state of health of the minors, but has assured that they are being carefully watched. "We are monitoring them and later we will be able to share the most accurate information," she mentioned. MarroquÃ­n has pointed out that it is not yet known what causes this disease, which has already resulted in many probable cases around the world. "There are different theories and in a percentage of cases, slightly less than 30% [higher in some studies - Mod.LL], a respiratory virus has been isolated in parallel, which is called adenovirus 41," she explained [adenovirus 41 is typically associated with gastroenteritis and more rarely respiratory symptoms. - Mod.JH] "We still do not have the certainty that this is the agent that is causing the inflammation of the liver," she pointed out.

Although the cause of the acute childhood hepatitis cases is unknown, they are mainly being reported in children under 16 years of age, the official highlighted. "That is why it is very important that we are attentive to any sign or symptom that may lead us to suspect that a child may develop hepatitis," she indicated. "Children with hepatitis develop, associated with diarrhea and vomiting, abdominal pain and a yellowish coloration both in the skin and in the mucous membranes. The conjunctiva of the eyes looks a little yellow and the skin also looks yellow," she described.

The WHO has warned on [2 May 2022] that the increase in cases of acute childhood hepatitis of unknown origin is a "very urgent" issue. According to the international organization, the disease has spread in 20 countries and possible infections are being investigated in another 13, after the 1st 10 cases were reported in the UK on [5 Apr 2022].

[Byline: Maria Julia Castaneda]

