******
[4] Greece
Date: Thu 12 May 2022
Source: Greek Reporter [abridged, edited]
https://greekreporter.com/2022/05/12/greece-acute-hepatitis-children/


Three children in Greece diagnosed with acute hepatitis
-------------------------------------------------------
The Greek National Heath Organization (EODY) announced on Thursday [12 May 2022] that 3 children had been diagnosed with acute hepatitis in Greece. The EODY announced that after conducting a thorough investigation, they found 3 children who fit into the WHO's criteria as likely cases of acute hepatitis.

Out of the 3 children, 2 experienced stomach pain and vomiting, and the 3rd was asymptomatic, but the hepatitis was found during routine testing. All 3 children are healthy and in good condition.

Greek health authorities have been on high alert since late April [2022] following a mysterious spike in cases of acute hepatitis in children around Europe. Cases of the illness that causes liver inflammation in children have been recorded across the world, including in North America, Asia, and Europe.

Researchers have found that 2 illnesses -- adenovirus and COVID-19 -- have a strong link to cases of acute hepatitis but are not present in all cases, as the 3 children in Greece all tested negative for the diseases. Additionally, the children, much like in other cases, tested negative for the 5 hepatitis viruses: hepatitis A, B, C, D, and E.

Parents are advised to look out for jaundice, or the yellowing of eyes and skin, dark urine, and pale stool in their children, as they are all indicators of hepatitis.

[Byline: Anna Wichmann]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[These 3 cases were seemingly milder and 1 was asymptomatic. It is unclear why that child was even tested. It is said in the post that all 3 tested negative for adenovirus and SARS-CoV-2 but the adenovirus PCR positivity may depend on whether whole blood or plasma is used and it is not stated if the SARS-CoV-2 testing was PCR, antigen or antibody testing. The report of an asymptomatic case, if it winds up being a documented case of whatever is or are causing this entity, could suggest there are many more subclinical cases in children and perhaps adults. - Mod.LL]

******
[5] Risk related to COVID-19 burden
Date: Thu 12 May 2022
Source: International Journal of Infectious Diseases [edited]
https://www.ijidonline.com/article/S1201-9712(22)00290-9/fulltext


Citation: Nishiura H, Jung S-M, Hayashi K: High population burden of omicron variant (B.1.1.529) is associated with the emergence of severe hepatitis of unknown etiology in children. Int J Infect Dis. DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijid.2022.05.028
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Abstract
--------
Objectives: In industrialized countries that have experienced major extensive epidemics of omicron (B.1.1.529), substantial fraction of the population was exposed including children.

Methods: Statistical association between the detection of at least one hepatitis case among children and the cumulative number of omicron cases (B.1.1.529) was examined. A total of 38 countries that belong to the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development and Romania were included in the analysis.

Results: Of the total of 39 countries, 12 detected at least one hepatitis case, and their confirmatory diagnoses of omicron cases from 1 Dec 2021 to 27 Apr 2022 ranged from 4.4 to 11.9 million. Among the remaining 27 countries, the cumulative number ranged from 0.5 to 5.5 million cases. Countries with hepatitis cases experienced a higher population burden of omicron cases (p = 0.013).

Conclusions: Prior exposure to omicron variant may be associated with an increased risk of severe hepatitis among children, indicating a critical need to conduct cofactor studies.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[In item 5, while there was a correlation with reported absolute numbers of COVID-19 cases and the appearance of this as yet undefined pediatric hepatitis when the authors looked at COVID-19 cases per 100 000 population, the differences were not signficant: "Comparing the cumulative incidence of omicron cases per capita between 2 groups, 12 countries with at least 1 hepatitis case again yielded greater mean incidence (21 868 per 100 000) than the other 27 countries (18 532 per 100 000), but the difference was not significant (t = 0.866, p = 0.40)."

The joint ECDC-WHO report is the 1st to clearly show an epi-curve plotting 1st day of symptoms of cases over time and seems to show a prominent rise in cases starting at epidemiological week 9 (starting 25 Feb 2022) and peaking at week 15 (starting 8 Apr 2022) with a subsequent drop. Most of the cases, therefore, are not from looking back to months ago. The drop, as they note, may relate to a delay in reporting. The report also provides, to some degree, data on SARS-CoV-2 antibody testing and reported 14 of 19 being positive. This could lead to some more support to the theory that, in the absence of adenovirus DNA in the liver specimens tested, SARS-CoV-2 ought to be responsible for the hepatitis as a late phenomenon which is akin to what may be the case with MIS-C. The numbers are small and there is no parallel data on SARS-CoV-2 antibodies in control children without this hepatitis.

The Nishiura paper mentioned in a previous post is now in press as a Short Communication in IJID, and could be interpreted as supporting a role of SARS-CoV-2 in the undefined hepatitis reports but the data was seemingly only statistically significant with reported absolute cases of COVID-19 in countries, not cases per 100 000 population. Even if there were a strong statistical association with past infection with SARS-CoV-2 in the development of severe hepatitis in children (again there did not seem to be a control group in the ECDC-WHO data), this could be a "post hoc ergo propter hoc" scenario, that is "if it happened after, it must be due to" which is proven as faulty reasoning many times for attributing cause and effect. The COVID-19 vaccines are not implicated as most children were young enough not to be eligible for immunization.

The adenovirus data presented in the joint ECDC/WHO report certainly expands the information with 73 of 106 samples using whole blood adenovirus PCRs being found positive (68%). Previous metagenomic data from the UKHSA did not show any adenovirus DNA in the liver specimens. This might suggest the hypothesis that adenovirus (primarily serotype 41) could be, in conjunction with another trigger in the immune system (recent SARS-CoV-2 infection perhaps), at work. The finding of adeno-associated virus 2 in the UK in liver tissue using metagenomics remains unclear as previously discussed.

To date, minimal peer-reviewed studies on this growing outbreak have been published. ProMED awaits more information including blood and liver metagenomics, CDC data comparable with WHO/ECDC/UKHSA, more evidence for past COVID-19 infection, and screening of asymptomatic household contacts for elevated aminotransferases. Survey data from 12 May 2022 in Eurosurveillance suggested a signal for increased undefined pediatric hepatitis in certain countries but not all in Europe and Asia but no parallel data seems to have been published from the USA. Importantly, the epicurve published today (13 May 2022) by ECDC-WHO certainly shows a peak in numbers using the day of onset of symptoms beginning in late February 2022 so most of the newly reported cases were not from earlier in the time span being looked at. - Mod.LL]
